'''''The New Jedi Order: Agents of Chaos I: Hero's Trial''''' is a [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]] novel written by [[James Luceno]]. It is the fourth volume of the ''[[Star Wars: The New Jedi Order]]'' series, following [[The New Jedi Order: Dark Tide II: Ruin|''Dark Tide II: Ruin'']] and preceding [[The New Jedi Order: Agents of Chaos II: Jedi Eclipse|''Agents of Chaos II: Jedi Eclipse'']]. It was first published in paperback by [[Del Rey]] in [[August]] [[2000]].

==Publisher's summary==
''Merciless attacks by invincible alien force have left the New Republic reeling. Dozens of worlds have succumbed to occupation or annihilation, and even the Jedi Knights have tasted defeat. In these darkest of times, the noble Chewbacca is laid to rest, having died as heroically as he lived&mdash;and a grief-stricken Han Solo is left to fit the pieces of his shattered life back together before he loses everything: friends, family, and faith.''

''Refusing help from Leia or Luke, Han becomes the loner he once was, seeking to escape the pain of his partner's death in adventure&hellip;and revenge. When he learns that an old friend from his smuggling days is operating as a mercenary for the enemy, he sets out to expose the traitor. But Han's investigation uncovers an even greater evil: a sinister conspiracy aimed at the very heart of the New Republic's will and ability to fight&mdash;the Jedi.''

''Now Han must face down his inner demons and, with the help of a new and unexpected ally, honor Chewbacca's sacrifice in the only way that matters&mdash;by being worthy of it.''

==Plot summary==
The [[Yuuzhan Vong War]] grows worse for the New Republic as the [[Yuuzhan Vong]] continue to advance toward [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]], the heart of the New Republic, with its latest [[First Battle of Obroa-skai|capture]] of the information [[Planet/Legends|planet]] of [[Obroa-skai/Legends|Obroa-skai]]. And what's worse is that citizens of [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]] are starting to side with the Vong, becoming a group known as the [[Peace Brigade]]. Seeing the Jedi as a threat, the Vong decide to unleash [[Priestess/Legends|Priestess]] [[Elan]] and her aide/pet, [[Vergere]], to pretend to be defectors from the Vong so she can get close to the Jedi and unleash a spore that will not only kill her but everyone around her, and she is ordered to do it against the Jedi.

Meanwhile, Han Solo, with the loss of Chewbacca, separates himself from his family and friends and becomes a loner. Along the way, Han meets up with an old smuggler ally named [[Roa]] (whose wife, [[Lwyll]], died because of the Vong) who says he knows someone who is heavily involved with the Vong's plans, whose name, unknown to either Han or Roa, is [[Reck Desh]], another past ally of Han's who was actually good friends with Chewbacca. So Han and Roa meet up with a contact at a [[Space station/Legends|space station]] at [[Ord Mantell/Legends|Ord Mantell]] named [[Fasgo]], and Han gets into a fight with a mercenary named [[Bossk/Legends|Bossk]], an old enemy of Han who hated [[Wookiee/Legends|Wookiees]], therefore, he hated Chewbacca. Han, Roa, Fasgo and Bossk are transported to a prison but are freed by [[Big Bunji/Legends|Boss Bunji]], a smuggler who knew Han and said he owed him a great deal after saving his business with the death of [[Jabba Desilijic Tiure/Legends|Jabba]] the [[Hutt/Legends|Hutt]] more than two decades earlier.

However, around the same time, Elan and Vergere allow themselves to be captured by New Republic forces on [[Wayland/Legends|Wayland]], and feint attacks there, and later on Ord Mantell, are meant to prove that Elan and Vergere are indeed on the Republic's side now. However, at the [[Battle of Ord Mantell (Yuuzhan Vong War)|Battle of Ord Mantell]], Roa and Fasgo are captured by Vong forces, and Han escapes the space station of the planet with several other people and [[Droma]], an alien whose species is called the [[Ryn/Legends|Ryn]], where it is revealed that Ryn are hated by the galaxy. After the feint attack at Ord Mantell, the refugee and New Republic survivors from the battle, including Han and Droma, board the ''Queen of Empire'', a large pleasure yacht whose next stop is at [[Bilbringi system/Legends|Bilbringi]]. However, Elan and Vergere happen to have boarded the ship so that when it goes to Coruscant and Elan makes her false treaty with the New Republic and Jedi, she will kill all of the Jedi who meet with her using the spores.

Meanwhile, Han and Droma began to form a mutual friendship. Later, the Vong's plans for defeating the Jedi become foiled when a spy for the Vong among the New Republic believed Elan and Vergere are actual defectors, like the rest of the Republic, and tips off the Peace Brigade. A certain team in the Brigade, lead by Reck Desh, invade the ''Queen of Empire'' to capture Elan and Vergere and bring them back to their masters, but when the Vong are quickly informed of it, a [[Battle of Bilbringi (Yuuzhan Vong War)|battle]] for the ship takes place between the New Republic and the Yuuzhan Vong. After Elan and Vergere are taken by Desh and his troops, the members of the Brigade strike team are killed by some of Elan's spores, and when Han and Droma show up to save the two "defectors," Han figures out Elan and Vergere are still on the Vong's side. Elan decides to use more of the spores to kill Han. Fortunately, Han is saved by a [[Miniature transpirator|device]] on a [[survival tool]] that his youngest son, [[Anakin Solo|Anakin]], gave him which was made by Chewbacca years earlier. It provides Han breathable air, thus saving him from the spores. Elan, therefore, dies by herself, having failed her mission to destroy the Jedi. As for Vergere, she gives Han and Droma some tears of hers that she states are able to heal [[Mara Jade Skywalker]]'s disease that is slowly killing her from the inside, which of course was thanks to the Yuuzhan Vong, and Vergere escapes.

After the battle at the ''Queen of Empire'', Han vows that he will help Droma reunite with his family, who are some of the many refugees of the New Republic fleeing from the Yuuzhan Vong.

==Continuity==
The working titles for the books of the ''Agents of Chaos'' series were ''Solo Crusade'' and ''The Crooked Sky''. In the original outline of the first novel, the [[Information broker/Legends|information broker]] on the [[Ord Mantell/Legends|Ord Mantell]] [[Space station/Legends|space station]] was to be [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]], but concerns that the book was adding too many characters caused Fett to be written out and replaced with [[Big Bunji/Legends|Big Bunji]], an incidental character mentioned in [[Brian Daley]]'s [[Star Wars: The Han Solo Adventures|Han Solo novels]]. Fett would not appear in [[Star Wars: The New Jedi Order|''The New Jedi Order'']] series until the final book, [[The New Jedi Order: The Unifying Force|''The Unifying Force'']] ([[2003]]).<ref name="ERC" />

A longtime friend of the late Daley, author [[James Luceno]] included many nods to Daley's influential trilogy, including the reappearance of [[Roa]], first seen in [[Han Solo's Revenge]] ([[1979]]). In the outline, Roa was to [[Death/Legends|die]] during the [[Yuuzhan Vong]] attack on the [[Jubilee Wheel (space station)|Jubilee Wheel]], but his fate changed as the novel developed. A detour in Han and Roa's search for the [[Ryn City|Ryn]] takes them to [[Ruan]], where they meet a [[Droid/Legends|droid]] who looks and asks an awful lot like the [[BLX labor droid|labor droid]] [[BLX-5|Bollux]] from Daley's Han Solo trilogy, but the text is deliberately vague as to the droid's identity.<ref name="ERC" /> 

In the initial story outline for ''The New Jedi Order'' series, the [[Refugee/Legends|refugee]] plot was described as a means of supplying the point of view of the underclasses, as the droids did in the first ''[[Star Wars]]'' movie.<ref name="ERC" /> 

